***Introduction: Project overview and objectives:

Develop a machine learning model to predict median house prices in California as a classification problem using socioeconomic and geographical features like median income, housing age, total rooms, population, and location (latitude/longitude)

Goal: Build an accurate model to help stakeholders (investors, policymakers, home buyers) make informed decisions about the housing market.

***Q3:feature engineering:

# Feature engineering
house_rec <-recipe(~., data = house_data) %>%
  step_log(median_income ,total_rooms, total_bedrooms, population, households) %>%
  step_impute_median(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_impute_mode(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  step_zv(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_novel(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_other(all_nominal_predictors(),threshold = 0.05 ) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% 
  step_corr(all_predictors(),threshold = 0.9) %>% 
  step_naomit(everything())

***Q4: clustring: we will use U-MAP for dimensionality reduction then k-means for clustering

**U-MAP:

library(umap)       
## Warning: package 'umap' was built under R version 4.4.2
library(cluster)
## 
## Attaching package: 'cluster'
## The following object is masked from 'package:tidyclust':
## 
##     silhouette
# Prep and bake the recipe to get the preprocessed data
preprocessed_data <- house_rec %>% 
  prep() %>%                     # Prepare the recipe
  bake(new_data = NULL)          # Extract the preprocessed data as a tibble

# Extract numeric columns and convert to a matrix
numeric_data <- preprocessed_data %>% 
  select(where(is.numeric)) %>%  # Select only numeric columns
  as.matrix()                    # Convert to a matrix

# Apply UMAP to the numeric matrix
umap_fit <- umap(numeric_data, n_components = 2, random_state = 42)

# Extract UMAP embeddings
umap_embeddings <- umap_fit$layout %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  rename(UMAP1 = V1, UMAP2 = V2)
## Warning: The `x` argument of `as_tibble.matrix()` must have unique column names if
## `.name_repair` is omitted as of tibble 2.0.0.
##  Using compatibility `.name_repair`.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.
# Add UMAP embeddings to the preprocessed data
preprocessed_data <- preprocessed_data %>% 
  bind_cols(umap_embeddings)

**K-means:

# Apply k-means clustering
set.seed(42)
kmeans_fit <- kmeans(umap_embeddings, centers = 3)  # 3 clusters

# Add cluster labels to the dataset
preprocessed_data <- preprocessed_data %>% 
  mutate(Cluster = as.factor(kmeans_fit$cluster))

# Visualize the clusters
ggplot(preprocessed_data, aes(x = UMAP1, y = UMAP2, color = Cluster)) +
  geom_point(size = 2, alpha = 0.8) +
  labs(title = "UMAP Projection with Clusters",
       x = "UMAP Component 1",
       y = "UMAP Component 2") +
  theme_minimal()

Using k means we have 3 clusters To know the different characteristics of each cluster we have to Compute mean values of features for each cluster

# Compute mean values of features for each cluster
cluster_summary <- preprocessed_data %>% 
  group_by(Cluster) %>% 
  summarise(across(where(is.numeric), mean, na.rm = TRUE))

  house_fit43 %>% collect_predictions() %>% 
    roc_curve(truth = price_category, .pred_above) %>% 
    mutate(Model ="Boosting")
)

this is a plot of all the roc curves to know wich model is the best for modeling so we can order them : . Boosting (AUC = 93.77%) . random forest (AUC = 93.53%) . bagging (AUC = 93.06%) . KNN (AUC = 92.7% ) . SVM (AUC = 91.67%) . logistic regression (AUC = 91.44%)

So the best model is boosting with AUC = 93.77% and its curve is the closest to the top left
